stylometry: A decision tree gives a complete scenario of how a decision is made. It uses probabilities and monetary values to calulate the best soltuion with the options available. Decision trees can be used to figure out which investment may be best. For example, I may have a choice between three investments, a savings account, buying stock, a CD account. By using the probabilities of revenue gained, the amounts invested, and the percentage I would earn, I could figure out which decision would most likely lead to the most money and therefore is the correct answer. Precision tree actually figures out which branch is the best option leaving me no guess work. Decision trees are important because they visually show the step by step scenario of how each decision will affect the outcome and how to obtain the desired outcome. Also in this example, a savings account, buying stock, and a CD account are decision nodes; while the probabilities of revenue from each are chance nodes.
